MCQ for Final years MBBS


Oral cancers




1.	 A 52-year-old male presents with a mass in the retromolar trigone area. He has a history of tobacco use. Biopsy reveals poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. Which feature on imaging is most indicative of an advanced stage of this cancer?
a)	Lesion size greater than 2 cm
b)	Involvement of the buccinator muscle
c)	Extension to the mandibular bone   *
d)	 Presence of cervical lymphadenopathy
e)	 Involvement of the skin
2.	 A 70-year-old female presents with a persistent ulcer on her gingiva and recent tooth mobility. She has no history of smoking. Biopsy confirms squamous cell carcinoma. What additional workup is essential to rule out a secondary source of the cancer?
a)	Chest CT scan
b)	PET-CT scan  *
c)	Bone scan
d)	MRI of the brain
e)	Abdominal ultrasound

3.	 A 55-year-old female with a long-standing history of oral lichen planus presents with an erosive lesion on her buccal mucosa. Biopsy reveals carcinoma in situ. Which treatment option is most appropriate?
a)	Observation and regular follow-up
b)	Topical corticosteroids
c)	Photodynamic therapy
d)	D. Surgical excision    *
e)	Radiotherapy

4.	 A 60-year-old male presents with a 3 cm ulcerated mass on the lateral tongue. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history . PET-CT scan reveals a single ipsilateral cervical lymph node metastasis measuring 2.5 cm. What is the most appropriate treatment plan?
a)	Surgery alone
b)	Chemotherapy alone
c)	Radiotherapy alone
d)	Surgery followed by radiotherapy
e)	Chemoradiotherapy  *

5.	  A 68-year-old female with a history of breast cancer treated with radiotherapy presents with a new mass on her upper gingiva. Biopsy reveals osteosarcoma. What is the most likely contributing factor to the development of this second malignancy?
a)	Genetic predisposition
b)	Tobacco use
c)	Alcohol consumption
d)	Prior radiotherapy  *
e)	Chronic irritation from dental prosthesis

6.	 A 72-year-old male presents with a firm mass in the anterior floor of the mouth. Biopsy reveals poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. Immunohistochemistry shows overexpression of p16. What is the most likely etiological factor for this tumor?
a)	HPV infection  *
b)	Tobacco use
c)	Alcohol consumption
d)	Betel nut chewing
e)	Chronic trauma

7.	 A 53-year-old male with a painless mass on the ventral surface of his tongue undergoes biopsy, which reveals adenosquamous carcinoma. This rare subtype is most commonly associated with which prognostic implication?
a)	Better prognosis than conventional squamous cell carcinoma
b)	Similar prognosis to HPV-positive oropharyngeal carcinoma
c)	Worse prognosis due to aggressive behavior *
d)	Reduced metastatic potential
e)	High response rate to immunotherapy

8.	 A 70-year-old female presents with a nodular lesion on her hard palate. Biopsy shows polymorphous low-grade adenocarcinoma. What is the typical treatment for this type of cancer?
a)	Radiotherapy alone
b)	Chemotherapy alone
c)	Wide local excision with clear margins  *
d)	Immunotherapy
e)	Observation
9.	 A 55-year-old male presents with a non-healing ulcer on the lateral border of his tongue that has been present for six months. He has a history of heavy smoking and alcohol consumption. Biopsy reveals squamous cell carcinoma. What is the most significant prognostic factor for this type of cancer?
a)	Tumor size
b)	Depth of invasion  *
c)	Location of the tumor
d)	Patientâ€™s age
e)	Presence of distant metastases

10.	  A 60-year-old female presents with a mass in the floor of her mouth. Imaging reveals a lesion invading the mandible. Biopsy confirms squamous cell carcinoma. Which surgical procedure is most appropriate for this patient?
a)	Wide local excision
b)	Marginal mandibulectomy
c)	Segmental mandibulectomy *
d)	Hemimandibulectomy
e)	Mandibular resection with reconstruction

Salivary Glands 


1.	 A 45 years old male presented with painless swelling in the preauricular region for 6 month. On examination the swelling is hard in consistency and non-tender.FNAC revealed  low-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma of the parotid gland. What is the preferred treatment modality for this patient?
a)	Total parotidectomy
b)	Radiation therapy alone
c)	Chemotherapy with cisplatin and docetaxel
d)	Superficial parotidectomy *
e)	Observation 

2.	 A 40-year-old female presents with intermittent swelling in the submandibular region for 6 months. The swelling increases during meal time . On examination there is firm swelling in the submandibular region. The clinical diagnosis of  recurrent sialadenitis of the submandibular gland is made.  What is the recommended treatment to manage her condition?
a)	Antibiotics and warm compresses
b)	Excision of the submandibular gland  *
c)	Radiation therapy
d)	Salivary gland massage
e)	Intravenous fluids 
3.	A patient with a history of recurrent pleomorphic adenoma undergoes surgical excision of a parotid gland tumor. What is the primary goal of surgery in this case?
a)	Symptom relief
b)	Complete tumor resection *
c)	Palliation
d)	Lymph node dissection
e)	Biopsy for diagnosis 


4.	 A 60-year-old male presents with hard swelling in the floor of mouth. The Biopsy revealed  a high-grade adenoid cystic carcinoma involving the sublingual gland. What is the most appropriate initial treatment approach?
a)	Chemotherapy
b)	Surgical excision with adjuvant radiation *
c)	Radiotherapy alone
d)	Targeted therapy with cetuximab
e)	Supportive care 
5.	  A patient is diagnosed with a parotid gland tumor suspected to be a Warthin tumor. What is the recommended treatment of choice for this lesion?
a)	Surgical excision *
b)	Chemotherapy
c)	Radiation therapy
d)	Observation
e)	Antibiotics 
6.	A 55-year-old male with recurrent submandibular sialolithiasis is unresponsive to conservative measures. What is the next step in management?
a)	Intravenous antibiotics
b)	Salivary gland massage
c)	Surgical removal of the stone *
d)	Radiation therapy
e)	Observation 
7.	 A patient is diagnosed with a malignant salivary gland tumor involving the palate and adjacent tissues. What is the primary treatment modality of choice?
a)	Chemotherapy
b)	Radiotherapy alone
c)	Surgical resection with adjuvant therapy *
d)	Targeted therapy with tyrosine kinase inhibitors
e)	Supportive care 
8.	 A 50-year-old female is found to have recurrent sialadenitis of the parotid gland. What is the definitive treatment to prevent further episodes?
a)	Systemic corticosteroids
b)	Parotidectomy *
c)	Antibiotics
d)	Sialogogues
e)	Lifestyle modifications 
9.	 A patient presents with a deep-lobe parotid gland tumor with suspected malignancy. What imaging modality is most useful for preoperative evaluation?
a)	Chest X-ray
b)	Ultrasound
c)	CT scan
d)	MRI *
e)	PET scan 
10.	 A 65-year-old male with recurrent sublingual gland inflammation is refractory to medical therapy. What is the next step in management?
a)	Radiation therapy
b)	Sialoendoscopy
c)	Surgical excision *
d)	Chemotherapy
e)	Observation





